<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-154-774  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 154 774.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>3D  Dec 1989 n20 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A tale of mice and desktop users. (graphical user interfaces andcomputer-aided design)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pipes, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-aided design (CAD) packages can only have so muchfunctionality, so as computers become more powerful, moreresources can be expended on the user interface to make it easierto interact with the systems.andP;  The Macintosh interface came out ofthe Smalltalk project in the 1970s at the Xerox Palo Alto ResearchCenter; it uses windows in which data is cut and pasted, icons andpull-down menus.andP;  It is usually an easy transition from theMacintosh environment to CAD systems, although such popular CADpackages as AutoCAD and VersaCAD were written initially for the PCenvironment.andP;  X-windows has become the de facto interface standardfor workstations because of its portability, operating systemindependence, network transparency and ability to supportconcurrent display of multiple applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     User InterfaceWindowingGraphical User InterfaceMenusSoftware DesignComputer-Aided DesignMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>